evidence:
Verified across three fetched Firecracker source files (raw.githubusercontent.com, main branch).

1) Boot-protocol selection — src/vmm/src/arch/x86_64/mod.rs, load_kernel():
"let mut boot_prot: BootProtocol = BootProtocol::LinuxBoot;
 if let PvhBootCapability::PvhEntryPresent(pvh_entry_addr) = entry_addr.pvh_boot_cap {
     entry_point_addr = pvh_entry_addr;
     boot_prot = BootProtocol::PvhBoot;
 }"
=> default is LinuxBoot; PVH chosen ONLY when PvhBootCapability::PvhEntryPresent. An ELF without the PVH note leaves boot_prot = LinuxBoot. Confirms "only when present, otherwise LinuxBoot; without note guaranteed long-mode entry." The XEN_ELFNOTE_PHYS32_ENTRY attribution is correct: that note is what the linux_loader ELF loader detects to set pvh_boot_cap = PvhEntryPresent. mod.rs comment also confirms the hvm_start_info/rbx claim: "This will be stored at PVH_INFO_START address, and %rbx will be initialized to contain PVH_INFO_START prior to starting the guest, as required by the PVH ABI."

2) Register state — src/vmm/src/arch/x86_64/regs.rs:
- setup_regs() PVH arm: "rbx: super::layout::PVH_INFO_START, rip: entry_point.entry_addr.raw_value()".
- configure_segments_and_sregs() PVH arm: "sregs.cr0 = X86_CR0_PE | X86_CR0_ET; sregs.cr4 = 0;" (constants: X86_CR0_PE=0x1, X86_CR0_ET=0x10). LinuxBoot arm: "sregs.cr0 |= X86_CR0_PE; sregs.efer |= EFER_LME | EFER_LMA;" (= 64-bit long mode).
- setup_sregs(): "if let BootProtocol::LinuxBoot = boot_prot { setup_page_tables(...) }" => page tables (and CR0.PG via X86_CR0_PG, CR4.PAE) are set up only for LinuxBoot, so PVH boots with paging OFF. Test validate_segments_and_sregs PVH branch asserts: "sregs.cr0 & X86_CR0_PE != 0 && sregs.cr0 & X86_CR0_ET != 0" and "assert_eq!(0, sregs.cr4)".

3) rbx value — src/vmm/src/arch/x86_64/layout.rs: "pub const PVH_INFO_START: u64 = 0x6000;" => rbx = 0x6000. Confirmed.

Every detail (PvhEntryPresent gating, default LinuxBoot/long mode, 32-bit protected mode with paging off, cr0=PE|ET, cr4=0, rbx=0x6000 hvm_start_info) is exactly supported with no overclaim. No version/date assertions are made that could be mis-scoped.
